ED BRIDGE.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Washington County, New York|Washington County]]\n| 1858\n| 161\n| [[Battenkill]]\n| Listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1978.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==18 identified by Peter Folk==\nMore modern or otherwise not-as-authentic covered bridges in New York State also exist.  Peter Folk lists the following 18 bridges:<ref>[http://www.bridges-covered.com/new_york.html \"Covered Bridges of New York\", by Peter Folk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108214727/http://www.bridges-covered.com/new_york.html |date=2007-11-08 }} includes non-historic examples as well.</ref>\n* Waldbillig Bridge, in Albany County\n* Voorheesville School Bridge, in Albany County\n* Munson Bridge in Broome County\n* Thomas E. Kelly Bridge in Cattaragus County\n* Erpf Bridge in Delaware County\n* Fort Ticonderoga / Kissing Bridge, in Essex County\n* Morehouse Bridge in Fulton County\n* Old Forge Bridge in Herkimer County\n* Frontenac or North Country Bridge, in Jefferson County\n* Americana Village Bridge, in Madison County\n* [[Roydhouse Bridge]], in Oneida County, {{Coord|42|53|43.74|N|75|18|2.45|W|name=Roydhouse Bridge}}\n* [[Schoharie Bridge]], in [[Schoharie County, New York|Schoharie County]]\n* Ludlow Greens Bridge, in Suffolk County {{Coord|40|56.55|N|72|17.47|W|name=Ludlow Greens Bridge}}\n* Grahamsville Bridge, in Sullivan County\n* Friendship Manor Bridge, in Ulster County\n* Myers Bridge, in Ulster County\n* Cambridge Bridge, in Washington County\n* Granville Bridge, in Washington County\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n* Dale J. Travis Covered Bridges. [http://www.dalejtravis.com/cblist/cbny.htm NYSCB Credits]. Retrieved May 20, 2013.\n* Covered Bridges of the Northeast USA. [http://www.coveredbridgesite.com/ny/ny_home.html NYSCB Credits]. Retrieved May 20, 2013.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070629172410/http://www.nycoveredbridges.org/page6.html \"Overview of the History of Covered Bridges in New York State\" by Raymond Smith]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New York covered bridges}}\n[[Category:Covered bridges in New York (state)|*]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in New York (state)|Covered bridges]]\n[[Category:New York (state) transportation-related lists|Covered bridges]]\n[[Category:Lists of covered bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in New York (state)|Bridges]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of covered bridges in New York State'''.\n\nThe New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation identifies 29 [[covered bridges]] in [[New York State]] as historic, but these are not all listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}  The [http://www.nycoveredbridges.org/ New York Society of Covered Bridges] lists 24 historic covered bridges.<ref>[http://www.nycoveredbridges.org/ New York Covered Bridge Society] state map with locations, and a photo of each historic bridge</ref>\n\nOne of the NRHPs, [[Old Blenheim Bridge]], has further been declared to be a [[National Historic Landmark]] and also has described by a [[Historic American Engineering Record]].  It may be the longest single-span covered bridge in the United States or in the world.{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\n==24 identified by New York Society of Covered Bridges==\n(ordered by counties):\n\n'''The following is a list of 24 of the historic  New York State [[covered bridge]]s.'''\n <!--BE VERY CAREFUL WHEN REVISING THIS TABLE. Make appropriate corrections or add new bridges only. Do not change overall format of table or its sortability. --> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" |Name\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" class=unsortable |Image\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" |Location<br>{{ref label|Location|A|A}}\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" |Year Built\n!